SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT THIS SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this "Agreement"), dated as of July 18, 2023, by and among Desert Peak Energy Center, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Owner"), as owner, Desert Peak Energy Storage I, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Desert Peak Energy Storage I"), and Desert Peak Energy Storage II, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Desert Peak Energy Storage II", collectively, with Desert Peak Energy Storage I, the "Licensees", each a "Licensee"). Owner and each of the Licensees may be referred to herein individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties." Capitalized terms used herein and not otherwise defined shall have the meanings ascribed to such terms in the LGIA (as such term is hereinafter defined). This Agreement shall be effective as of the date specified by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (such date, the "Effective Date").
RECITALS
WHEREAS, Desert Peak Energy Storage I owns, is developing and, upon completion, will operate a battery energy storage system with an expected nameplate capacity of approximately 325 MWac / 1300 MWh having the right to deliver up to 325 MWac at the Point of Interconnection (the "Desert Peak Energy Storage I Project");
WHEREAS, Desert Peak Energy Storage II will own and operate a battery energy storage system with an expected nameplate capacity of approximately 75 MWac / 300 MWh having the right to deliver up to 75 MWac at the Point of Interconnection (the "Desert Peak Energy Storage II Project", and collectively with Desert Peak Energy Storage I Project, the "Projects", and each a "Project");
WHEREAS, Owner is a party to a Large Generator Interconnection Agreement (the "LGIA"), by and among itself, Southern California Edison Company ("SCE") and California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO"), pursuant to which Owner has the right to receive Interconnection Services (as defined in the LGIA) for one or more generating facilities with the aggregate capacity not to exceed 400 MW at the Point of Interconnection;
WHEREAS, Owner owns, leases and/or operates certain personal property, real property, fixtures, easements, equipment and facilities described in Exhibit A attached hereto (the "Shared Facilities") that are necessary for the interconnection of each Project to the electric transmission system of SCE; and
WHEREAS, Owner desires to grant to the Licensees the right to utilize the Shared Facilities, on the terms and conditions set forth herein, so that they may receive the service from Owner that each Licensee requires to deliver its energy to the Point of Interconnection under the LGIA (as defined in the LGIA), and which Agreement together with the LGIA will establish the terms and conditions by which Owner will enable each Licensee to receive the service from Owner that it requires to deliver their energy to the Point of Interconnection under the LGIA;
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereby agree as follows:
AGREEMENT
1. TERM; EARLY TERMINATION
1.1. Term: The term of this Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date and shall continue in effect until terminated (a) by mutual agreement of the Parties or (b) pursuant to Section 1.2.
1.2. Early Termination: This Agreement shall, with respect to any Licensee, automatically terminate without further action by any Party hereto and without further liability of the terminating Licensee to the other Parties hereto or any non-terminating Party to the terminating Licensee, on the date that the terminating Licensee or its successors and assigns have permanently ceased operation of its Project for the production of electric energy.
2. GRANT OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS
2.1 Grant: During the term of this Agreement and on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof, Owner hereby grants to each of the Licensees, respectively, the nonexclusive right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities as may be reasonably necessary in connection with such Licensee's ownership, operation and maintenance of its respective Project.
2.2 Essential Nature: Owner hereby acknowledges that Licensees' rights to access and utilize the Shared Facilities described in Exhibit A attached hereto are essential to the production of electric energy by the respective Projects.
2.3 Vesting: The right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities granted to each of the respective Licensees hereunder shall vest in the Licensees as a contracting party hereunder without any transfer of title or leasehold interest in the Shared Facilities.
2.4 Reimbursement: In addition to any other amounts required to be paid by Licensees pursuant to Section 4.1 hereof, each of the Licensees is obligated to reimburse Owner for any and all modifications made to the Shared Facilities necessary to accommodate such Licensee's use of such facilities; provided that each Licensee shall only be responsible for such reimbursement related to its Project.
3. NATURE OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS
3.1 Limitation on Grant: Owner grants to each of the Licensees the right to utilize the Shared Facilities, but only to the extent that such right does not (a) limit in any material respect the ability of Owner to perform its obligations under any material agreement, as the same may be hereafter modified or amended, that Owner has entered into, or enters into after the date hereof, or (b) adversely affect the operations or profitability of Owner in any material respect.
3.2 Assignment or Transfer of Rights: Except as set forth in Section 8.7, none of the Licensees may assign or transfer the rights granted hereunder, or grant any permission, license, right of way or similar right to the rights granted hereunder, without the prior written consent of Owner (not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed).
3.3 Prior Written Consent: Owner shall not take any action that results in the forbearance, foreclosure, termination or alteration of any of the Licensees access to, utilization of or reliance upon the Shared Facilities, without the prior written consent of each of the Licensees (not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed).
4. MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES
4.1 Allocation of Certain Costs and Expenses: Owner shall be responsible for the ownership or possession, operation, inspection, maintenance, repair, alteration relocation, improvement and replacement of the Shared Facilities. Pursuant to the LGIA, Owner is also responsible for certain expenses ("Interconnection Agreement Costs"), including potential costs under Section 10.5 of the LGIA for operations and maintenance expenses. The Parties hereby agree that the costs and expenses of the operation, inspection maintenance, repair, alteration, relocation, improvement and replacement of the Shared Facilities and potential costs under the LGIA shall be allocated among the Parties as follows: (a) from the Effective Date until Desert Peak Energy Storage II energizes, 100% to Desert Peak Energy Storage I, and (b) from the date Desert Peak Energy Storage II energizes, 81.25% to Desert Peak Energy Storage I, and 18.75% to Desert Peak Energy Storage II. Each Licensee shall pay its respective allocation (specified above) of such costs and expenses to Owner within ten (10) days of receipt from Owner of written notice specifying such costs and expenses. Owner and each of the Licensees acknowledge that as between the Parties hereto and any purchaser of power from any Licensee, the Parties hereto are responsible for all costs and charges directly caused by, associated with, or allocated to a Licensee or Owner under the LGIA, this Agreement and the CAISO Tariff, in connection with the interconnection of any Project to the CAISO Controlled Grid.
4.2 Successor Agreement: In the event that the Projects are no longer operated and maintained by the same entity for any reason, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts to negotiate mutually agreeable terms and execute a mutually agreeable agreement (or amendment to this Agreement) that specifies the division of responsibilities of the entities providing operation and maintenance services associated with the Shared Facilities.
5. CHANGE IN LAW
5.1 Change in Law: In the event that a change in the laws or regulations applicable to Owner, any of the Licensees, either Project, or this Agreement requires the amendment, modification or replacement of this Agreement in order to satisfy any applicable federal, state or local regulatory requirements, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts to negotiate and implement mutually agreeable terms to accomplish such amendment, modification or replacement.
6. CERTAIN COVENANTS
6.1 Authority and Operational Abilities: Each of the Parties represents, as of the Effective Date, and covenants for the term of this Agreement, that such Party has the legal authority and operational abilities to fulfill its obligations under this Agreement.
6.2 Payment of Certain Studies, Upgrades and Facilities: In the event that a Project at any time shall pay, fund or post as security pursuant to the LGIA any amounts, facilities, upgrades, or studies to the extent arising as a result of the interconnection of any other Project, the Project in connection with whose interconnection such costs arose shall promptly pay and reimburse on demand all such costs to the Project that shall have initially paid, funded or posted the same as security.
6.3 Observance of LGIA: Each Party shall exercise its rights and perform its obligations under the LGIA which have been assigned to it or its Project in a manner that is reasonable and not discriminatory against the other Parties. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, during the term of this Agreement, each Party agrees to:
6.3.1 Operate its respective Project in accordance with Good Utility Practice, Applicable Laws and Regulations and Applicable Reliability Standards, in each case as defined in the LGIA, and in a manner consistent with the terms of the LGIA.
6.3.2 Observe and facilitate Owner's compliance with all provisions of the LGIA and the CAISO Tariff to which Owner is subject (and all insurance requirements, operational limits, operating guides, operating procedures and reliability standards and requirements applicable by virtue thereof, including, without limitation, Appendix H to Appendix CC of the CAISO Tariff or its equivalent successor) as it relates to its respective Project, including Owner's securing and maintaining in full force and effect all required CAISO agreements, certifications, approvals and the CAISO Resource ID that is to be used for each of the Projects;
6.3.3 Not take any action (or refrain from taking any action) which would result in a breach of the LGIA;
6.3.4 Use all commercially reasonable efforts to promptly resolve any technical issues arising in connection with the operation of its respective Project that might reasonably be expected to result in a default under the LGIA, and if such default occurs, to promptly cure such default in accordance with the terms of the LGIA;
6.3.5 Comply with all instructions, as may be communicated by Owner, in order to ensure compliance with the provisions of the LGIA with respect to its respective Project; and
6.3.6 Provide each other Party with all reasonable information regarding the operation and condition of its respective Project required for each other Party to maintain compliance with the terms and conditions of the LGIA.
6.4 Adjustments to Cost Allocations:
6.4.1 If an operational issue arises at one of the Projects that could be reasonably expected to result in a material breach by Owner of the LGIA, or by any Party of this Agreement (an "Adverse Event"), Owner shall curtail the Project that is causing the Adverse Event to the extent necessary to avoid the Adverse Event. Owner will cease curtailment upon the affected Party's cure of the operational issue causing the Adverse Event.
6.4.2 If, as a direct result of an Adverse Event, Owner incurs any Interconnection Agreement Costs, the Project that has caused such Adverse Event shall be solely responsible for reimbursing Owner for any such Interconnection Agreement Costs. In the event that both Projects are responsible for the Adverse Event, and to the extent that responsibility for such Adverse Event can be accurately allocated between the Projects, each Project shall be responsible for its allocable portion of the applicable Interconnection Agreement Costs. If, however, it is not reasonably possible to accurately allocate such responsibility, each Project responsible for the Adverse Event will be liable for its respective pro rata share of such Interconnection Agreement Costs (provided that, for this purpose, the denominator used in determining the pro rata share shall be the aggregate capacity of the Projects responsible for the Adverse Event only).
6.4.3 Notwithstanding any other provision contained herein, if any Interconnection Agreement Costs are incurred by Owner, which Interconnection Agreement Costs are incurred primarily to benefit the Desert Peak Energy Storage I Project or the Desert Peak Energy Storage II Project, then, to the extent such Interconnection Agreement Costs can be accurately allocated between the Desert Peak Energy Storage I Project and the Desert Peak Energy Storage II Project, each of Desert Peak Energy Storage I and Desert Peak Energy Storage II shall be responsible for its allocable portion of the applicable Interconnection Agreement Costs. If, however, it is not reasonably possible to accurately allocate such responsibility between Desert Peak Energy Storage I and Desert Peak Energy Storage II, then such Interconnection Agreement Costs shall be allocated among the Parties in accordance with Section 4.1 of this Agreement.
6.4.4 Without limiting Section 8.8 hereof, in the event that any Party is required to pay to any third party any cost, expense, or liability, which cost, expense, or liability is allocable to another Party pursuant to this Section 6.4, such responsible Party(ies) shall indemnify, defend and hold such paying Party harmless from any and all such costs, expenses, or liabilities, including, without limitation, attorney fees.
6.5 Allocation of Capacity; Priority of Curtailment: Except as otherwise provided in Section 6.4, Owner shall at all times make available or allocate interconnection capacity to each Licensee's respective Project in an amount at the Point of Interconnection not to exceed 325 MW for Desert Peak Energy Storage I and 75 MW for Desert Peak Energy Storage II. Except as otherwise provided in Section 6.4, but notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, in the event of curtailment pursuant to the LGIA (or pursuant to applicable operating guides or applicable reliability standards and requirements), the Parties agree that the Projects shall be curtailed on a pro rata basis based on installed capacity of the respective Projects then in operation, except when such pro rata allocation would be in violation of the applicable curtailment instruction.
6.6 Agreement to Cooperate: Each Party agrees to reasonably cooperate with the other Parties so that, subject to the terms of this Agreement, each Project benefits from the full utilization and enjoyment of the Shared Facilities as is necessary for the efficient operation of each such Project.
6.7 Right to Correct, Remedy, Mitigate or Cure: Each Party shall have the right to correct, remedy, mitigate or otherwise cure any omission, failure, breach or default of any other Party where such omission, failure, breach or default could be reasonably anticipated to have a material adverse effect on such Licensee's obligations under its respective power purchase agreement, the LGIA or this Agreement.
6.8 Title Insurance Claims Related to a Battery Energy Storage System: To the extent Owner maintains a title insurance policy which specifically insures any battery energy storage system, and for which a related survey describes the as-built improvements for such battery energy storage system, each Party hereby agrees that the proceeds of any claim under such title insurance policy which are related to such battery energy storage system shall be paid directly to the Licensee who owns and operates such battery energy storage system.
6.9 Metering Protocol: A revenue metering system for, and the allocation of losses and generation among, the Projects is included in Exhibit B.
7. GRANT OF RIGHT OF USE
7.1 Use of Property: Owner hereby grants to each Licensee a separate nonexclusive right of use (each, a "License", and collectively, "Licenses") over the corresponding portions of real property described on Exhibit C attached hereto (the "Property"), for the purpose of the development, construction, operation, use, and management of its respective battery energy storage system, together with associated rights to access such facilities. Each License includes rights to maintain and repair the battery energy storage system. Each Licensee accepts the applicable License in its current "AS IS, WHERE IS, WITH ALL FAULTS" condition including but not limited to any patent or latent defects or conditions existing with respect to the applicable Property.
8. MISCELLANEOUS
8.1 Relationship of Parties: (a) The Parties do not intend to create hereby any joint venture, partnership, association or any other entity for the conduct of any business, and (b) nothing herein shall be deemed to authorize any Party to act on behalf of any other Party.
8.2 Non-Interference: Subject to Section 3.3, each Party agrees not to interfere with the reasonable and necessary utilization of the Shared Facilities by any other Party as permitted hereunder.
8.3 Modification and Amendment: The terms of this Agreement may only be modified or amended in a writing signed by all Parties hereto.
8.4 Waiver: The failure of a Party to insist upon or enforce strict performance of any of the provisions of this Agreement or to exercise any rights or remedies under this Agreement shall not be construed as a waiver or relinquishment to any extent of such Party's right to assert or rely upon any such provisions, rights, and remedies in that or any other instance; rather, the same shall be and remain in full force and effect.
8.5 Enforceability: Any provision of this Agreement which is prohibited or unenforceable in any jurisdiction shall, as to such jurisdiction, be ineffective only to the extent of such prohibition, but shall be effective to the extent of such remaining provisions hereof. 8.6 Transfer of Shared Facilities: Except as set forth in Section 8.7, Owner may not transfer, sell, assign or sub-lease its ownership interest in the Shared Facilities or any portion thereof without the prior written consent of each of the Licensees.
8.7 Assignment: No Party may assign its rights or obligations hereunder without the prior written consent of each other Party; provided that any Party may collaterally assign this Agreement to any entity, or such entity's agent, in connection with a financing or a refinancing that is directly or indirectly secured in whole or in part by the Shared Facilities or the Projects, as applicable, and any actual assignment or transfer to another party arising from the realization upon any such collateral assignment (including, without limitation, any purchaser at a foreclosure sale) shall also be permitted without the prior written consent of any other Party. This Agreement shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of successors and permitted assigns of the Parties hereto. Additionally, no Licensee may assign or transfer its rights or obligations under this Agreement or under the LGIA without the prior written consent of the counterparty to a power purchase and sale agreement entered into by such Licensee.
8.8 Indemnification: Each Party shall indemnify, defend and hold the other Parties harmless from any and all damages, losses, claims, including claims and actions relating to injury to or death of any person or damage to property, demand, suits, recoveries, costs and expenses, court costs, attorney fees, and all other obligations by or to third parties, arising out of or resulting from the indemnifying Party's performance, or non-performance of its obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA, except in cases of gross negligence or intentional wrongdoing, by the indemnified party. However, in no event shall any Party be liable to the other Parties under any provision of this Agreement for any losses, damages, costs or expenses for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, or punitive damages, including but not limited to loss of profit or revenue, loss of the use of equipment, cost of capital, cost of temporary equipment or services, whether based in whole or in part in contract, in tort, including negligence, strict liability, or any other theory of liability; provided, however, that damages for which a Party may be liable to the other Parties under another agreement will not be considered to be special, indirect, incidental, or consequential damages hereunder.
8.9 Governing Law: This Agreement shall be governed by and constructed in accordance with the laws of the State of California, without regard to its conflict of laws provisions.
8.10 Inspection of Records: Each Party shall have access to any records concerning the Shared Facilities held by any other Party upon reasonable notice and at reasonable times.
8.11 Section Headings: The section headings in this Agreement are for convenience of reference only and shall not modify, define, expand, or limit any of the terms or provisions hereof.
8.12 Counterparts: This Agreement may be executed in one or more counterparts, each of which when so executed shall be deemed an original, and all of which when taken together shall constitute one and the same instrument.
8.13 Resolution of Disputes: Any dispute or controversy arising under this Agreement, its application or interpretation ("Dispute") shall be settled definitively and exclusively in accordance with the following procedure:
8.13.1 The Dispute will first be reviewed by one member of management designated for the purpose of each Party. It is the intention of the Parties that the designated managers shall, within thirty (30) days of designation, devise a mutually agreeable solution for acceptance by all Parties.
8.13.2 If the designated managers are unable to devise an acceptable solution within thirty (30) days, or if the Parties do not accept the solution proposed, the Dispute shall be submitted to the Chief Executive Officer ("CEO") of NextEra Energy Resources, LLC for resolution. The CEO may resolve the Dispute personally or appoint an individual or a committee to resolve the Dispute. In delegating his authority, the CEO may impose any deadlines or direct the utilization of such procedures, if any, as he deems appropriate. The decision of the CEO or his designee shall be final and binding on each of the Parties.
8.14 Third-Party Beneficiaries: Each of the Parties hereto hereby grants to SCE and CAISO, as parties to the LGIA, the right, as third-party beneficiaries of this Agreement, to enforce the Parties' obligations under Sections 6.2 and 6.3 hereunder, and acknowledges and agrees that Sections 6.2 and 6.3 are expressly for benefit of SCE, CAISO and the Parties.
8.15 Specific Performance: The Parties hereto may demand specific performance of this Agreement. Each Party hereby irrevocably waives any defense based on the adequacy of a remedy at law and any other defense which might be asserted to bar the remedy of specific performance.
8.16 Future Facilities: The Parties hereto agree to amend this Agreement to grant to Desert Sands Energy Storage I, LLC, the entity owning CAISO Queue Position Number 1758, and the entity owning CAISO Queue Position Number 2049, upon energization of their respective facilities, the right to utilize the Shared Facilities, on the terms and conditions set forth herein, so that they may receive the service from Owner that each requires to deliver its energy to the Point of Interconnection under the LGIA (as defined in the LGIA), and further agree to amend the cost allocation set forth in Section 4.1 herein to reflect a pro rata allocation based on the total megawatts that is permitted to be delivered to the Point of Interconnection by each facility in their respective LGIAs. .

Interconnection Summary Desert Peak Energy Center, LLC is a Battery Storage (BESS) facility located in Riverside County, CA. There is one (1) substation at this site with three (3) transformers and BESS resources behind each transformer. Transformer T1 and T2 will be one CAISO re- source, hereafter referred to as Marvel and Transformer T3 will be a second CAISO resource, hereafter referred to as Marvel 2. Point of Interconnection is the SCE Devers Substation. The Marvel BESS is CAISO project 16SAS0071. The Marvel 2 BESS is CAISO project 22NGR22669. This document covers both projects 16AS0071 (Marvel) and 22NGR22669 (Marvel 2). B. Project Topology The Desert Peak Energy Park Project consists of three Battery Energy Storage System units, with each unit being served by its own step-up transformer. The Point of interconnection is the Devers Substation, and all BESS units charge from the Grid. There are no Transformer or Transmission line losses accounted for by the metering on site, as all metering is connected to the 230kV bus.
11040 White Rock Rd, Suite 100 Rancho Cordova, CA 95827 • P: 888.858.3441 • www.ulteig.com B1. Station Totalizing Meters
11040 White Rock Rd, Suite 100 Rancho Cordova, CA 95827 • P: 888.858.3441 • www.ulteig.com B2. Marvel Transformer T1 Meters
11040 White Rock Rd, Suite 100 Rancho Cordova, CA 95827 • P: 888.858.3441 • www.ulteig.com B3. Marvel Transformer T2 Meters
11040 White Rock Rd, Suite 100 Rancho Cordova, CA 95827 • P: 888.858.3441 • www.ulteig.com B4.Marvel 2 Transformer T3 Metering C. Metering Topology Each of the three transformers have meters installed on the High Voltage (HV) metering points. NEER metering is installed at the boundary of the energy center to meter the totalized generation and load of the energy center. Each HV BESS metering set consists of a primary and secondary CAISO meter, a NEER owner meter, and a SCE utility meter. The BESS metering circuit has an additional
11040 White Rock Rd, Suite 100 Rancho Cordova, CA 95827 • P: 888.858.3441 • www.ulteig.com meter specifically used to monitor system frequency (Frequency Control) for frequency regulation. The SCE meters installed at each metering set are to record retail loads. Station Service Load (SSL) for the energy center is a feeder connected to transformer T2. The SSL furnishes power to the control house for operations of the center. A Load sheet calculates the total load at 79.25kW. This load is considered a retail load by SCE and is measured by the utility metering installed on the control house. The CAISO and NEER meters net the SSL from the gross delivered or received loads. D. Metering Methodology All meters for the Desert Peak Energy center record delivered and received energy depending on the operating status of the associated BESS unit. When a BESS unit is charging, the metering is recording delivered energy, likewise when the BESS unit is generating the metering is recording received energy. E. MV-90 and CAISO Standard Meter Load Profile Channel Assignments All Desert Peak Energy Center Metering Facilities are installed and configured in such a manner to comply with the following CAISO requirements: Each meter shall be programmed to the CAISO Interval Data Channel configuration standard set forth in the Business Process Manual for Metering, Version 23, Revised 06/20/2022, Attachment B: Technical specifications, Section A2 Metering facilities must be installed and configured in such a manner to comply with the following CAISO requirements: • Channel 1 must record active power (kWh) delivered by the CAISO controlled grid. • Channel 2 must record reactive power (kVARh) delivered by the CAISO controlled grid. • Channel 3 must record reactive power (kVARh) received by the CAISO controlled grid. • Channel 4 must record active power (kWh) received by the CAISO controlled grid. Additionally, BESS revenue meters are required by CAISO to not record retail metering data, colloquially referred to as when the BESS is idle, or BESS IDLE mode. Therefore, BESS meters have additional channel 5 and 6 interval data channels.
11040 White Rock Rd, Suite 100 Rancho Cordova, CA 95827 • P: 888.858.3441 • www.ulteig.com • Channel 5 must record active power (kWh) delivered by the CAISO controlled grid when the meter is in BESS IDLE mode. • Channel 6 must record reactive power (kVARh) delivered by the CAISO controlled grid when the meter is in BESS IDLE mode. F. Resource Configuration F1. CAISO-ME BESS Resource configuration 16AS0071 The BESS resource 16AS0071 (Marvel) charging load or generation is the total of the 2 BESS CASIO metering sets, below. 16AS0071 BESS (Main) = 5920856+5920857 16AS0071 BESS (Backup) = 5920858+5920859 F2. CAISO-ME BESS Resource configuration 22NGR22669 The BESS resources of 22NGR22669 generation and wholesale charging loads are recorded by the meters below. 22NGR22669 BESS (Main)= 5920864 22NGR22669 BESS (Backup) = 5920865 All BESS meter measurements include BESS Auxiliary loads used for battery conditioning. These loads are the sum of the BESS charging load, and the BESS Auxiliary load, and are netted out of the generation load as the loads are served by the BESS feeder cir- cuit. Station Service load, also referred to as Control House power, is considered a retail load by the Southern California Edison Company (SCE). Shared Facility Agreements are in place between the two resources to facilitate the sharing of the control house facilities, in- cluding the utility billing of the Station Service load, which are netted from the CAISO and NEER metering to eliminate double bill- ing of these loads. An Automatic Transfer Switch (ATS) switches the Control house Load to emergency generation or a backup feed
11040 White Rock Rd, Suite 100 Rancho Cordova, CA 95827 • P: 888.858.3441 • www.ulteig.com from SCE in the event of an outage. The meters are programmed with an input from the ATS that turns off any netting of SSL when the ATS is not in normal mode. G. Meter Compensation Equations There are no meter compensation equations for this project. H. Meter Implementation NextEra’s Desert Peak Energy Center BESS project design includes the Schneider Electric ION8650 meters for revenue metering purposes. The ION8650 meter is ANSI 0.2% Class Accurate with excellent calculation capabilities. The ION8560 meters and 0.15% accuracy class metering Instrument Transformers installed at the facility are acceptable by CAISO standards for revenue metering applications. CAISO Metering Entity (CAISO-ME) revenue meters are installed at each BESS metering point to monitor and record the energy flows in and out of the plant. NextEra Owned (NEER) meters are installed at the HV and BESS metering points to monitor, and record energy flows in and out of the plant. The NEER meters serve as a check meter to the revenue meters and to provide data and analog outputs to the plant control equipment. Additionally, each BESS has a Nexus 1500+ meter installed to provide high speed frequency information to the plant controller for grid frequency support. The NEER ION 8650 metering is programmed with identical metering parameters as compared to the revenue metering. The Nexus 1500+ meters are programmed with the same instrument transformer values as the revenue meters to measure frequency and transmit frequency data to the plant controller system. The meter communication interfaces are as shown on the Communications Block diagrams submitted to CAISO, “16AS0071 CommBlock Ver 1” and “22NGR22669 CommBlock Ver 1”, respectively.

Revenue Meter Description Revenue meters for the Resurgence PV generators are classified as CAISO Metering Entity (CAISO-ME) per section 10.2 of the CAISO Tariff. I1. Marvel Transformer 1 Metering Marvel BESS 1 CAISO-ME Primary Meter (230MT1-2) The Marvel BESS 1 Primary meter is designated 230MT1-2, CASIO meter 5920856, and will be connected to the NEER Desert Peak Network. This will provide the path for MV-90 access as well as communications to the CAISO RIG for telemetering. Marvel BESS 1 CAISO-ME Backup Meter (230MT1-3) The Marvel BESS 1 Primary meter is designated 230MT1-3, CASIO meter 5920858, and will be connected to the NEER Desert Peak Network.
